{{Refimprove|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{Flagicon|Greece}} "Horepse" | image = | caption = | year = 1997 | country = Greece | artist = [[Marianna Zorba]] | as = | lyricist = Manolis Manousselis | composer = Manolis Manousselis | conductor = Anacreon Papageorgiou | languages = [[Greek language|Greek]] | place = 12th | points = 39 | prev = Emis Forame To Himona Anixiatika | prev_link = Emis Forame To Himona Anixiatika | next = Mia Krifi Evesthisia | next_link = Mia Krifi Evesthisia }}
'''Horepse''' ([[Greek alphabet|Greek script]] '''Χόρεψε''', [[English language|English]] translation: "Dance") was the [[Greece|Greek]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1997]], performed in [[Greek language|Greek]] by [[Marianna Zorba]].
Rumor has it that the music was originally composed by Chris Spheeris as an instrumental and that the lyrics were later added by Manolis Manouselis. This is a false rumor. Manousselis wrote the entire song.<ref>http://diggiloo.net/?info.1997gr#artists</ref> It is true that Spheeris wrote a song called "Horepse" but the similarity between that song and the one of Manousselis ends there.
The song was performed seventeenth on the night (following [[Sweden]]'s [[Blond (band)|Blond]] with "[[Bara hon älskar mig]]" and preceding [[Malta]]'s [[Debbie Scerri]] with "[[Let Me Fly]]"). At the close of voting, it had received 39 points, placing 12th in a field of 25.
The song is about the power of dance to rejuvenate people.
It was succeeded as [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greek representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|1998 Contest]] by [[Thalassa (band)|Thalassa]] with "[[Mia Krifi Evesthisia]]".
