{{distinguish|text=the [[Norwegian Military Academy]] (''Krigsskolen'')}}

The '''Norwegian Military College''' ({{lang-no|Den militære høyskole}}) was a military educational institution in Norway.

It was established on 16 February 1817, with headquarters at [[Akershus Fortress]]. It was originally meant for artillery and engineer officers, but in 1826 it was expanded to include [[navy|naval]] officers as well&mdash;however, not many naval officers actually attended.<ref name=archive>{{cite news|url=http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/publikasjoner/nett/handbok-ra/forsvaret/hoyskole.html |title=Den militære høyskole 1817-1940 |publisher=[[National Archival Services of Norway]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=18 May 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504191840/http://www.arkivverket.no/arkivverket/publikasjoner/nett/handbok-ra/forsvaret/hoyskole.html |archivedate=May 4, 2008 }}</ref>

There were several changes in the length of the education offered at the Military College. From 1901 a two-year course was offered, educating personnel to the General Staff. The school had been mandatory for General Staff members since 1850. The school saw its demise in 1940,<ref name=archive/> the same year as Norway was [[Operation Weserübung|invaded]] and [[occupation of Norway by Nazi Germany|occupied by Germany]].

